---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Hero from "../../components/ui/Hero.astro";
import PageSection from "../../components/ui/PageSection.astro";
import CardGrid from "../../components/ui/CardGrid.astro";
import Card from "../../components/ui/Card.astro";
import CTAStrip from "../../components/ui/CTAStrip.astro";
import Pill from "../../components/ui/Pill.astro";
import Prose from "../../components/ui/Prose.astro";
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Retrieval: ACL-gated Corpus Search on Aeira | Sparcle"
  description="Retrieval is Bolt's indexed-corpus integration surface, powered by Aeira. 103 in-house data ingestors plus the Airbyte bridge (~350 sources) and any MCP-compliant server. ACLs gate the data at retrieval, not as a postprocess filter. Hybrid search and customer-extensible ranking. Production today, public docs landing."
  canonical="https://sparcle.app/docs/retrieval/"
>
  <main class="page-retrieval">
    <Hero
      eyebrow="Documentation &middot; Mode 3 &middot; Production today"
      title="Retrieval."
      lede="The indexed-corpus integration surface. Powered by Aeira. Connectors ingest your sources, Aeira indexes them, ACLs gate the data at retrieval. Fast at query time, cheap per query."
    >
      <a href="/docs/integrate" class="btn btn-primary btn-lg">
        See all three surfaces
      </a>
      <a href="/docs/utilities" class="btn btn-secondary btn-lg">
        Start with Apps today &rarr;
      </a>
    </Hero>

    <PageSection stripe="b" width="prose">
      <div class="roadmap-banner">
        <Pill variant="brand" size="sm">Production today &middot; docs landing</Pill>
        <p>
          The Retrieval engine is in production with a deep data-ingestor
          catalog, ACL-aware hybrid search, and customer-tunable ranking. This
          page covers what ships today. The full public API reference and
          authoring docs land here as the surface stabilizes. See
          <a href="/architecture">the architecture page</a> for Aeira's
          ACL-aware index in more depth, or <a href="/integrations">the
          integrations catalog</a> for vendor coverage.
        </p>
      </div>
    </PageSection>

    <PageSection
      eyebrow="Capabilities"
      title="What Retrieval ships today."
      lede="Concrete capabilities running in customer deployments. The public authoring API and detailed docs are still being stabilized; the engine underneath is not."
      stripe="a"
    >
      <CardGrid cols={2}>
        <Card title="103 in-house data ingestors">
          Ingestors cover knowledge sources, ticketing, CRM, code, files,
          observability, and data warehouses. New ingestors land weekly.
          Data ingestors are distinct from MCP servers, which power Apps and
          Agent tool calls. Many vendors offer both.
        </Card>
        <Card title="Airbyte bridge for the long tail">
          Beyond the in-house ingestor catalog, the Airbyte bridge extends
          Retrieval to hundreds more SaaS and database sources. Anything in
          the Airbyte ecosystem can become a Retrieval source.
        </Card>
        <Card title="Hybrid search">
          Keyword, vector, and entity-graph traversal in one query. The engine
          picks the right mix per query. Customers do not have to choose a
          search mode; they get the best of all three.
        </Card>
        <Card title="Customer-extensible ranking, trust, authority">
          Relevance, recency, source quality, trust signals: all shapable
          through policy code. The engine ships sensible defaults; customers
          extend with their own rules. Authorization stays platform-enforced
          and is never customer-overridable.
        </Card>
      </CardGrid>
    </PageSection>

    <PageSection
      eyebrow="Architectural commitments"
      title="The shape of Retrieval."
      lede="Four things hold across every release of the surface. Everything else is implementation that will evolve."
      stripe="b"
    >
      <CardGrid cols={2}>
        <Card title="ACLs gate at the index">
          Authorization is an architectural property, not a postprocess filter.
          Documents the user cannot read never enter the candidate set. Ranking
          and authority are kept separate from authorization.
        </Card>
        <Card title="Authority is customer-shapable. Authorization is not.">
          Ranking, relevance, recency, and trust signals are yours to shape.
          Access control is enforced by the platform and is not customer-overridable.
          Two contracts, one floor.
        </Card>
        <Card title="Aeira is the engine">
          Aeira is Sparcle's retrieval and policy engine. It owns the index,
          the authorization graph, and the audit chain. The same code paths
          run in the free single-user install and in production org deployments.
        </Card>
        <Card title="No data leaves your perimeter">
          The index lives where you deploy Bolt. Embeddings are generated by
          a model you choose. Sparcle does not host a hosted-corpus tier.
          The data stays where you put it.
        </Card>
      </CardGrid>
    </PageSection>

    <PageSection
      eyebrow="Decision rule"
      title="When to reach for Retrieval."
      stripe="a"
      width="prose"
    >
      <Prose>
        <p>
          Use Retrieval when the answer lives across a large corpus and the
          right document isn't predictable from the question. If the answer
          is in one of three known APIs, it's an App. If the answer is one of
          ten thousand documents you've written internally over five years,
          it's Retrieval.
        </p>
        <p>
          Retrieval pairs naturally with the other two surfaces. An Agent
          can use Retrieval as a tool to ground its reasoning. An App can
          link to a Retrieval result as a typed row. The three surfaces are
          composable, not exclusive.
        </p>
      </Prose>
    </PageSection>

    <CTAStrip
      variant="band"
      eyebrow="In the meantime"
      title="Apps is live. Retrieval shares its primitives."
      lede="The same identity, ACL, and audit-chain machinery you wire up for Apps today is what gates Retrieval tomorrow. Get the platform wired in now, light up Retrieval when the surface ships."
    >
      <a href="/docs/utilities/quickstart" class="btn btn-primary btn-xl">
        Try Apps today
      </a>
      <a href="/architecture" class="btn btn-secondary btn-xl">
        Read the architecture
      </a>
    </CTAStrip>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>

<style is:global>
  /* Same roadmap-banner treatment as /docs/agents. Scoped to the page so the
     two surfaces can diverge later without leaking into each other. */
  .page-retrieval .roadmap-banner {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: max-content 1fr;
    gap: 1rem;
    align-items: start;
    background: var(--bg-surface-solid);
    border: 1px solid var(--border-default);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--brand-primary);
    border-radius: var(--radius-md);
    padding: 1.1rem 1.3rem;
  }
  .page-retrieval .roadmap-banner > .pill {
    margin-top: 0.15rem;
  }
  .page-retrieval .roadmap-banner p {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: 0.98rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: var(--text-body);
  }
  @media (max-width: 600px) {
    .page-retrieval .roadmap-banner {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: 0.6rem;
    }
  }
</style>
